---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Hotel Stocks Dividend Analysis & 5-Year History",
  description: "Thinking of investing in hotel stocks? We analyze the exact dividend yields and history for MAR and HLT to see if they're actually worth holding.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": ["Article", "FAQPage"],
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do hotel stocks pay dividends?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, many hotel stocks like Marriott (MAR) and Hilton (HLT) pay dividends, though their yields tend to be lower than traditional dividend stocks, often sitting under 1.5% as they focus heavily on growth and share buybacks."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the dividend yield for Marriott (MAR)?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Marriott International (MAR) currently pays a dividend yield of approximately 0.96%, equating to an annual payout of around $2.52 per share based on recent distributions."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Did hotel stocks suspend dividends during the pandemic?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, nearly all major hotel stocks suspended their dividends in 2020 and 2021 due to the severe impact of global travel restrictions on their revenue."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Which is a better dividend stock, Hilton or Marriott?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Marriott generally offers a slightly higher dividend yield than Hilton. Hilton's yield often sits below 0.5%, as the company prioritizes aggressive share repurchases over cash payouts."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are hotel stocks good for income investors?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Hotel stocks are generally not considered ideal for pure income investors due to their low yields and cyclical vulnerability. They are better suited for investors seeking capital appreciation combined with modest dividend growth."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/hotel-stocks" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>HOTEL Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">An in-depth look at Marriott (MAR) and Hilton (HLT) dividend payouts.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>Investing in <strong>hotel stocks</strong> presents an intriguing dilemma. On one hand, you have massive, resilient cash-generating brands like Marriott International (MAR) and Hilton Worldwide (HLT) that operate asset-light franchise models. On the other, the cyclical nature of travel makes their dividends inherently volatile. Are these hospitality giants truly reliable dividend payers, or are they better suited for capital appreciation?</p>

      <h2>Current Dividend Yield and Payout Profile</h2>
      <p>When analyzing hotel stocks, investors often quickly realize that these are not your typical high-yield dividend payers like <a href="/utilities-stocks">utility stocks</a> or <a href="/reit-dividend-yields-2026">REITs</a>.</p>

      <div class="stats-grid">
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>Marriott (MAR) Yield</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">0.96%</p>
          <span class="badge neutral">Quarterly Payout</span>
        </div>
        <div class="stat-card">
          <h3>Hilton (HLT) Yield</h3>
          <p class="calc-result-value">0.27%</p>
          <span class="badge neutral">Quarterly Payout</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Currently, Marriott's trailing annual dividend yield sits at approximately 0.96%, equating to an annual payout of roughly $2.52 per share. Hilton offers an even lower yield of around 0.27%, representing an annual distribution of just $0.60 per share.</p>

      <h2>5-Year Dividend History</h2>
      <p>The 5-year history of hotel stocks is defined by the catastrophic impact of the 2020 pandemic. Both MAR and HLT entirely suspended their dividends in 2020 and 2021 as global travel ground to a halt. While they have since reinstated their payouts, their historical consistency was severely broken.</p>

      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Year</th>
              <th>Marriott (MAR)</th>
              <th>Hilton (HLT)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>2024</td>
              <td>$2.52</td>
              <td>$0.60</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2023</td>
              <td>$1.84</td>
              <td>$0.60</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2022</td>
              <td>$0.70</td>
              <td>$0.45</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2021</td>
              <td>$0.00</td>
              <td>$0.00</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>2020</td>
              <td>$0.48</td>
              <td>$0.15</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Dividend Growth Rate Analysis</h2>
      <p>Since reinstating their dividends in late 2022, the growth rates have superficially appeared massive (MAR grew its dividend by over 160% between 2022 and 2023). However, this is simply a return to the pre-pandemic baseline, not true compounding growth. Compared to reliable dividend growers like <a href="/dividend-aristocrats">Dividend Aristocrats</a>, hotel stocks fail to offer the steady, uninterrupted compounding that income investors crave.</p>

      <h2>Comparison to Category Average</h2>
      <p>When measuring hotel stocks against the broader consumer discretionary sector (which averages closer to 1.5%), MAR and HLT fall short. The reason is capital allocation: both management teams vastly prefer using excess free cash flow for aggressive share repurchases rather than taxable cash dividends.</p>

      <h2>Key Metrics and Fundamentals</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Marriott (MAR):</strong> Trades at a P/E ratio of roughly 26.4.</li>
        <li><strong>Hilton (HLT):</strong> Commands a steep premium with a P/E near 48.2.</li>
        <li><strong>Business Model:</strong> Both operate heavily franchised, "asset-light" models, meaning they don't own the physical real estate for most of their branded properties. This results in high margins and significant free cash flow generation.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="calculator-card">
        <h3>Hotel Stocks Dividend Reinvestment Calculator</h3>
        <p>Estimate the projected annual income from your shares.</p>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="shares">Shares Owned</label>
          <div class="input-wrapper">
            <input type="number" id="shares" value="100" min="1" step="1">
            <span class="suffix">shares</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="input-group">
          <label for="tickerSelect">Select Stock</label>
          <select id="tickerSelect" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.75rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary); font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 1.1rem;">
            <option value="2.52">Marriott (MAR) - $2.52/yr</option>
            <option value="0.60">Hilton (HLT) - $0.60/yr</option>
          </select>
        </div>

        <div class="calc-result">
          <span class="calc-result-label">Projected Annual Income</span>
          <div class="calc-result-value" id="projectedIncome">$252.00</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
          <summary>Do hotel stocks pay dividends?</summary>
          <p>Yes, many hotel stocks like Marriott (MAR) and Hilton (HLT) pay dividends, though their yields tend to be lower than traditional dividend stocks, often sitting under 1.5% as they focus heavily on growth and share buybacks.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>What is the dividend yield for Marriott (MAR)?</summary>
          <p>Marriott International (MAR) currently pays a dividend yield of approximately 0.96%, equating to an annual payout of around $2.52 per share based on recent distributions.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Did hotel stocks suspend dividends during the pandemic?</summary>
          <p>Yes, nearly all major hotel stocks suspended their dividends in 2020 and 2021 due to the severe impact of global travel restrictions on their revenue.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Which is a better dividend stock, Hilton or Marriott?</summary>
          <p>Marriott generally offers a slightly higher dividend yield than Hilton. Hilton's yield often sits below 0.5%, as the company prioritizes aggressive share repurchases over cash payouts.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Are hotel stocks good for income investors?</summary>
          <p>Hotel stocks are generally not considered ideal for pure income investors due to their low yields and cyclical vulnerability. They are better suited for investors seeking capital appreciation combined with modest dividend growth.</p>
        </details>
      </section>
    </section>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    function initHotelCalculator() {
      const container = document.querySelector('.calculator-card');
      if (!container || container.dataset.initialized === 'true') return;

      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('shares');
      const tickerSelect = document.getElementById('tickerSelect');
      const projectedIncome = document.getElementById('projectedIncome');

      function updateCalculator() {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const dps = parseFloat(tickerSelect.value) || 0;

        const income = shares * dps;
        projectedIncome.textContent = `$${income.toFixed(2)}`;
      }

      sharesInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalculator);
      tickerSelect.addEventListener('change', updateCalculator);

      container.dataset.initialized = 'true';
    }

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initHotelCalculator);
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initHotelCalculator);
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content {
      max-width: 900px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 2rem 1.5rem;
    }
    .hero {
      text-align: center;
      padding: 3rem 0 2rem;
    }
    .hero h1 {
      font-size: 2.2rem;
      font-weight: 800;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
      color: var(--accent-color);
    }
    .subtitle {
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      font-size: 1.1rem;
    }
    .content-section {
      margin-top: 2rem;
    }
    .stats-grid {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr));
      gap: 1.5rem;
      margin: 2rem 0;
    }
    .stat-card {
      background: var(--card-bg);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 1.5rem;
      text-align: center;
    }
    .stat-card h3 {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
    }
    .calc-result-value {
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 2rem;
      font-weight: 800;
      color: var(--accent-color);
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .badge {
      display: inline-block;
      padding: 0.25rem 0.75rem;
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      font-weight: 600;
      border-radius: 9999px;
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
    }
    .badge.neutral {
      background-color: rgba(148, 163, 184, 0.1);
      color: var(--text-secondary);
    }
    .table-container {
      overflow-x: auto;
      margin: 2rem 0;
    }
    table {
      width: 100%;
      border-collapse: collapse;
      background: var(--card-bg);
      border-radius: 12px;
      overflow: hidden;
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    }
    th, td {
      padding: 1rem;
      text-align: left;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    }
    th {
      background-color: rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.05);
      color: var(--accent-color);
      font-weight: 600;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      font-size: 0.85rem;
    }
    td {
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
    }
    tr:last-child td {
      border-bottom: none;
    }
    .calculator-card {
      background: var(--card-bg);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      border-radius: 12px;
      padding: 2rem;
      margin: 2.5rem 0;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
    }
    .calculator-card h3 {
      text-align: center;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .calculator-card p {
      text-align: center;
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }
    .input-group {
      margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    }
    .input-group label {
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
      font-weight: 600;
    }
    .input-wrapper {
      position: relative;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
    }
    .input-wrapper input {
      width: 100%;
      background: var(--bg-color);
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      color: var(--text-primary);
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;
      border-radius: 8px;
    }
    .input-wrapper input:focus, select:focus {
      outline: none;
      border-color: var(--accent-color);
    }
    .suffix {
      position: absolute;
      right: 1rem;
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      pointer-events: none;
    }
    .calc-result {
      margin-top: 2rem;
      padding-top: 1.5rem;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
      text-align: center;
    }
    .calc-result-label {
      color: var(--text-secondary);
      font-size: 0.95rem;
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .faq-section {
      margin-top: 3rem;
    }
    .faq-section details {
      margin: 1rem 0;
      padding: 1.25rem;
      background: var(--card-bg);
      border-radius: 8px;
      border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    }
    .faq-section summary {
      font-weight: 600;
      cursor: pointer;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      color: var(--text-primary);
    }
    .faq-section details p {
      margin-top: 1rem;
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
